<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
2.5-2.9 mm long (mean = 2.64 mm; n = 5); 2.78-3.0
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as wide. This species is distinguished by the unique elytral mycangium appearing as a distinctly impressed area immediately adjacent to the scutellum on each elytron; and declivity steeply sloping, occupying apical 1/4.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="similar species">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Similar species.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Reitter" authorityYear="1913" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Heteroborips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Heteroborips cryptographus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cryptographus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Heteroborips cryptographus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is distributed from Europe to the Russian Far East, and 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. indicus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="indicus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">H. indicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
China (Shaanxi, Shanxi, Sichuan), Japan, South &amp; North Korea, Russia (Far East, Kuril Is). Introduced and established in USA (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.4289/07-048.1" author="Hoebeke, ER" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="470 - 476" refId="B192" refString="Hoebeke, ER, Rabaglia, RJ, 2008. Xyleborus seriatus Blandford (Coleoptera: Curculionidae: Scolytinae), an Asian ambrosia beetle new to North America. Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington 110: 470 - 476, DOI: https://doi.org/10.4289/07-048.1" title="Xyleborus seriatus Blandford (Coleoptera: Curculionidae: Scolytinae), an Asian ambrosia beetle new to North America." url="https://doi.org/10.4289/07-048.1" volume="110" year="2008">Hoebeke and Rabaglia 2008</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="host">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Host plants.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Polyphagous attacking both conifers and angiosperms (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.4289/07-048.1" author="Hoebeke, ER" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="470 - 476" refId="B192" refString="Hoebeke, ER, Rabaglia, RJ, 2008. Xyleborus seriatus Blandford (Coleoptera: Curculionidae: Scolytinae), an Asian ambrosia beetle new to North America. Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington 110: 470 - 476, DOI: https://doi.org/10.4289/07-048.1" title="Xyleborus seriatus Blandford (Coleoptera: Curculionidae: Scolytinae), an Asian ambrosia beetle new to North America." url="https://doi.org/10.4289/07-048.1" volume="110" year="2008">Hoebeke and Rabaglia 2008</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The gallery system is unusual in lying between the bark and wood and not penetrating the wood. The parent female, larvae and pupae are all found together in communal chambers under the bark (
<bibRefCitation author="Murayama, J" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the Faculty of Agriculture, Yamaguti University" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="81 - 106" refId="B279" refString="Murayama, J, 1955. Supplementary notes on the scolytid-fauna of Japan. Bulletin of the Faculty of Agriculture, Yamaguti University 6: 81 - 106" title="Supplementary notes on the scolytid-fauna of Japan." volume="6" year="1955">Murayama 1955</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Nakashima, T" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Faculty of Agriculture, Hokkaido University" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="239 - 273" refId="B283" refString="Nakashima, T, Otomo, T, Owada, Y, Iizuka, T, 1992. SEM observations on growing conditions of the fungi in the galleries of several ambrosia beetles: (Coleoptera: Scolytidae and Platypodidae). Journal of the Faculty of Agriculture, Hokkaido University 65: 239 - 273" title="SEM observations on growing conditions of the fungi in the galleries of several ambrosia beetles: (Coleoptera: Scolytidae and Platypodidae)." volume="65" year="1992">Nakashima et al. 1992</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
